    isFeatured: false,
    content: `<h2>Why the Toilet Renovation Deserves More Attention Than It Gets</h2>
<p>Of all the rooms in an HDB flat, the toilet is the one most likely to be renovated multiple times during a homeowner's tenure. Tiles crack, waterproofing fails, fittings wear out, and aesthetics date quickly. Yet many Singapore homeowners underbudget and underplan their toilet renovation, leading to costly redos just a few years later.</p>
<p>The average cost of renovating one HDB toilet in 2025 ranges from <strong>S$4,500 to S$12,000</strong>, depending on size, materials, and scope of works. Getting it right the first time — especially the waterproofing — is a matter of doing things properly, not just cheaply.</p>

<div class="info-box"><strong>ℹ️ Did You Know:</strong> Water seepage from poorly waterproofed HDB bathrooms is one of the top three causes of neighbour disputes in Singapore. The Community Disputes Resolution Tribunal handles hundreds of such cases each year — most could have been avoided with proper waterproofing and a completed 24-hour ponding test.</div>

<h2>HDB Rules for Toilet Renovation</h2>
<p>Toilet renovation requires an HDB Renovation Permit because it involves wet area works and plumbing. Key rules:</p>
<ul>
<li>All floor and wall surfaces in the toilet must be waterproofed before tiling, to at least 300mm above floor level (1.8m for shower areas).</li>
<li>A 24-hour water ponding test must be conducted on the waterproofed floor before tiles are laid — this is not optional.</li>
<li>Floor finishes must have a minimum slip resistance rating of R9.</li>
<li>Existing floor drains cannot be relocated — only the drain cover can be changed.</li>
<li>The toilet door threshold (the raised lip at the entrance) must be maintained to prevent water spillage into the rest of the flat.</li>
<li>Plumbing works must be carried out by a licensed plumber.</li>
</ul>
<div class="warning"><strong>⚠️ Important:</strong> Skipping or rushing the waterproofing and ponding test is the single biggest cause of water seepage problems between HDB units. A leaking bathroom ceiling is one of the most common and expensive neighbour disputes in Singapore. Do not cut corners here.</div>

<h2>Cost Breakdown: What You're Paying For</h2>
<h3>Hacking (S$800–S$2,500)</h3>
<p>Removing existing tiles — floor, walls, and sometimes the shower screen area — is the first step. In older resale flats with multiple layers of tiles, hacking can be more expensive and create more debris. Disposal of debris is typically charged separately at S$200–S$600.</p>
<h3>Waterproofing (S$600–S$1,500)</h3>
<p>A proper waterproofing membrane applied in two coats to the floor and lower walls. Do not let your contractor skip the ponding test — this is where leaks are caught before they become your problem and your downstairs neighbour's problem.</p>
<h3>Tiling (S$1,500–S$5,000)</h3>
<p>Tile costs vary enormously: basic homogeneous tiles start at S$2–S$5 per sqft, while imported Italian or Spanish porcelain runs S$8–S$25 per sqft. A typical HDB toilet has 20–30 sqft of floor and 80–120 sqft of wall area. Tile installation labour: S$6–S$12 per sqft.</p>
<h3>Sanitary Ware (S$1,500–S$5,000)</h3>
<p>WC (toilet bowl): S$300–S$1,500. Wall-hung WC with concealed cistern: S$800–S$3,000. Basin with vanity cabinet: S$400–S$2,000. Shower mixer and rain head set: S$300–S$1,500. Shower screen (frameless glass): S$600–S$2,000.</p>
<h3>Accessories and Sundries (S$300–S$800)</h3>
<p>Towel bars, toilet roll holder, soap dispenser, mirror with storage, exhaust fan replacement, and lighting. These small items add up — budget properly for them.</p>

<hr>

<h3>Toilet Renovation Cost Summary by Scope</h3>
<div style="overflow-x:auto">
<table>
<thead><tr><th>Scope</th><th>Description</th><th>Estimated Cost</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Fittings refresh</td><td>Replace WC, basin, taps only — no tiling</td><td>S$1,500–S$3,000</td></tr>
<tr><td>Partial reno</td><td>New tiles + new fittings, retain layout</td><td>S$4,500–S$7,000</td></tr>
<tr><td>Full reno (mid-range)</td><td>Hack, waterproof, re-tile, all new fittings</td><td>S$7,000–S$10,000</td></tr>
<tr><td>Full reno (premium)</td><td>Large-format tiles, wall-hung WC, frameless screen, European fittings</td><td>S$10,000–S$15,000+</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>

<h2>Popular HDB Toilet Design Styles in 2025</h2>
<h3>The Hotel Bathroom Look</h3>
<p>Large-format tiles (600×1200mm or larger) in marble or stone-look porcelain, wall-hung WC with concealed cistern, frameless shower screen, and LED mirror with built-in storage. This look requires quality fittings and careful workmanship — grout lines must be perfectly aligned with large-format tiles. Budget: S$8,000–S$15,000 per bathroom.</p>
<h3>Warm Earthy Minimalism</h3>
<p>Terrazzo or warm beige stone-look tiles, matte black fittings, timber-look vanity, and soft warm lighting. Currently one of the most popular aesthetic directions for Singapore bathrooms. Budget: S$6,000–S$10,000 per bathroom.</p>
<h3>Classic Black and White</h3>
<p>White subway tiles with dark grout, black matte fittings, hexagonal mosaic floor tiles, and a period-inspired vanity. Timeless, easy to maintain, and always looks sharp. Budget: S$5,000–S$8,000 per bathroom.</p>

<blockquote>"Our contractor wanted to skip the ponding test to save a day. We insisted, and good thing — it failed. They found a pinhole in the membrane at the floor drain. Fixed before tiling, no issues since. Never skip the ponding test." — Homeowner, 4-room resale, Clementi</blockquote>

<div class="pro-tip"><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> For small HDB toilets (under 4 sqm), use large-format tiles with minimal grout lines. Counter-intuitively, bigger tiles make small spaces feel larger by reducing visual fragmentation. Avoid small mosaic tiles on the floor — they require significantly more grout, which is harder to keep clean in Singapore's humid conditions.</div>

<h2>The Shower Area: Wet vs Dry Zone Planning</h2>
<p>In Singapore's compact HDB toilets, separating the wet zone (shower) from the dry zone (WC and basin area) is important for practicality and longevity. Options:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Frameless glass panel or screen:</strong> The premium choice. No frame means no mold-trapping tracks. Cost: S$600–S$2,000.</li>
<li><strong>Shower curtain:</strong> Budget-friendly at S$30–S$150 but less elegant and requires regular cleaning and replacement.</li>
<li><strong>Step-down shower area:</strong> A slight depression in the shower floor area (30–50mm) keeps water contained without a physical barrier. Popular in minimalist designs but requires careful waterproofing.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How Long Should Your Toilet Renovation Take?</h2>
<p>For a straightforward HDB toilet renovation: hacking (day 1) → waterproofing and ponding test (days 2–5) → tiling (days 5–8) → plumbing and sanitary ware installation (days 8–12) → accessories and finishing (days 12–14). A quality toilet renovation takes approximately 2 weeks per bathroom. Be wary of contractors promising to complete it in under a week — they are likely skipping the ponding test or rushing the waterproofing.</p>`,
