    isFeatured: false,
    content: `<h2>The Art of Living Large in a Small HDB Flat</h2>
<p>Singapore has some of the world's most expensive and compact housing. A 2-room Flexi flat is 36–45 sqm; a 3-room flat is typically 65–75 sqm. Within these dimensions, Singaporeans must fit living, dining, sleeping, storage, and increasingly, working from home. The good news is that decades of innovative Singapore interior design have produced a remarkable body of knowledge about how to make small spaces live large — and these ideas actually work.</p>

<div class="info-box"><strong>ℹ️ Did You Know:</strong> Singapore's average HDB flat size has decreased over successive BTO generations — newer 4-room flats average 90 sqm, compared to 100+ sqm for 1990s-era flats. This makes smart space planning more important than ever for modern Singapore homeowners.</div>

<h2>1. Floor-to-Ceiling Wardrobes in Every Bedroom</h2>
<p>The gap between the top of a standard wardrobe and the ceiling is dead space in any small flat. Floor-to-ceiling built-in wardrobes capture this space for storage — seasonal items, luggage, spare bedding — while creating a visually cleaner room by eliminating the "shelf of dust" above conventional wardrobes. Cost: S$3,000–S$8,000 per bedroom.</p>

<h2>2. Murphy Beds (Wall Beds) for Multi-Use Rooms</h2>
<p>A Murphy bed folds into the wall when not in use, transforming a bedroom into a home office, study, or exercise space during the day. Cost: S$3,500–S$8,000 including carpentry surround.</p>

<h2>3. Sofa Beds for the Living Room</h2>
<p>For a 2-room or 3-room flat where a dedicated guest bedroom is not possible, a quality sofa bed in the living room solves the guest accommodation problem without consuming permanent floor space. Modern sofa beds from brands like Ligne Roset, King Living, or local upholstery specialists look and feel like proper sofas. Cost: S$1,500–S$6,000.</p>

<h2>4. Dining Tables That Fold, Extend, or Dual-Purpose</h2>
<p>A fold-down wall-mounted dining table that seats 2 normally and extends to 4 for guests takes up minimal space when folded. Alternatively, a counter-height kitchen island can serve as both prep surface and dining table with bar stools. Cost: S$800–S$3,000 for a quality fold-down or extension dining solution.</p>

<h2>5. Under-Stair Storage (for Maisonettes and Landed)</h2>
<p>For HDB Executive Maisonettes with internal staircases, the space under the stairs is premium storage real estate. Custom drawers, a wardrobe, or a compact home office neatly integrated under the staircase. Cost: S$2,000–S$6,000 for custom carpentry.</p>

<h2>6. Bed Platform with Full Under-Bed Storage</h2>
<p>A platform bed with a full set of hydraulic-lift storage drawers beneath — accessible from both sides — adds the equivalent of a large chest of drawers in storage volume without any additional floor footprint. Cost: S$2,000–S$4,500 for a queen-size platform with storage.</p>

<h2>7. Overhead Storage Above Doors and Corridors</h2>
<p>The space above door frames and along corridor walls (at 2.1–2.4m height) is almost universally wasted in HDB flats. Custom high-level cabinets in this space store rarely-accessed items — documents, holiday decorations, spare appliances. Cost: S$500–S$1,500 per linear metre of high-level storage.</p>

<h2>8. Mirrored Surfaces to Double Visual Space</h2>
<p>Mirrors do not add floor space but they convincingly create the visual impression of it. A full-height mirror on one bedroom wall, a mirrored wardrobe door, or a large mirror in the living room behind the sofa all create perceived depth and brightness. Mirrored wardrobe doors (sliding): S$1,500–S$4,000.</p>

<h2>9. Light Colours and Monochromatic Palettes</h2>
<p>Dark colours absorb light and make walls feel closer. Light, monochromatic colour schemes — where walls, ceiling, and trim are in the same or closely related light tones — make rooms feel seamlessly larger. This does not mean everything must be white; warm neutrals in the same tonal family create the same spatial expansion effect with more character.</p>

<h2>10. Open Concept Living-Dining-Kitchen</h2>
<p>Removing partition walls between the kitchen, dining, and living areas creates one unified, larger-feeling space instead of three cramped rooms. This is the most impactful single renovation decision for spatial expansion. HDB-compliant sliding glass door for the kitchen wet area maintains regulatory compliance. Cost of wall removal: S$800–S$2,500.</p>

<h2>11–20: More Space-Saving Strategies</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Nesting tables instead of a coffee table:</strong> Three nesting side tables take up half the floor space. S$200–S$800.</li>
<li><strong>Integrated storage benches at the entrance:</strong> Shoe storage + seating. S$800–S$2,500 custom carpentry.</li>
<li><strong>Wall-mounted floating furniture:</strong> Floating TV units, bedside tables, study desks free up floor space below. S$300–S$800.</li>
<li><strong>Transparent and acrylic furniture:</strong> Clear acrylic chairs take up visual zero space. S$80–S$300 each.</li>
<li><strong>Utilise the bomb shelter:</strong> Custom shelving turns it into a proper pantry or storage room. S$300–S$800.</li>
<li><strong>Pocket doors instead of swing doors:</strong> Eliminates 600–900mm clearance zone. S$800–S$2,000 per door.</li>
<li><strong>Vertical gardens and floor-to-ceiling shelving:</strong> Go vertical — custom bookshelf S$1,200–S$3,000.</li>
<li><strong>Hidden TV nook:</strong> Recessing the TV into a feature wall niche. S$1,500–S$4,000 custom carpentry.</li>
<li><strong>Thin-profile furniture:</strong> A 75cm-deep sofa instead of 95cm frees meaningful floor area.</li>
<li><strong>Smart decluttering:</strong> The most effective space-saving strategy costs nothing — ruthless, periodic decluttering.</li>
</ul>

<blockquote>"We turned our 3-room flat into what feels like a 4-room by opening the kitchen, going floor-to-ceiling with storage everywhere, and choosing a fold-out dining table. Guests never believe it's only 70 sqm." — Homeowner, 3-room resale, Toa Payoh</blockquote>

<hr>

<h3>Space-Saving Investment Value Guide</h3>
<div style="overflow-x:auto">
<table>
<thead><tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Cost</th><th>Spatial Impact</th><th>Best For</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Open concept kitchen</td><td>S$800–S$2,500 (hacking)</td><td>Very High</td><td>All HDB flat types</td></tr>
<tr><td>Floor-to-ceiling wardrobes</td><td>S$3,000–S$8,000/room</td><td>High</td><td>All bedrooms</td></tr>
<tr><td>Murphy bed</td><td>S$3,500–S$8,000</td><td>High</td><td>Dual-use rooms</td></tr>
<tr><td>Overhead corridor cabinets</td><td>S$500–S$1,500/m</td><td>Medium</td><td>HDB corridors</td></tr>
<tr><td>Pocket doors</td><td>S$800–S$2,000/door</td><td>Medium</td><td>Small rooms</td></tr>
<tr><td>Mirror wardrobe doors</td><td>S$1,500–S$4,000</td><td>Medium (visual)</td><td>All bedrooms</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>

<div class="pro-tip"><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Prioritise renovation investments that create permanent spatial benefits (built-in storage, pocket doors, open concept layout) over those that create merely visual benefits (mirrors, light colours). Real space is always more valuable than visual tricks — though the best small-flat renovations use both.</div>`,
