    heroImage: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1484154218962-a197022b5858?w=1200&q=85",
    author: "Rachel Chua",
    authorRole: "Renovation Specialist",
    isFeatured: false,
    content: `<h2>The Interview That Determines Your Renovation's Success</h2>
<p>Your initial consultation with a prospective interior designer is an interview — and you are the interviewer. Many Singapore homeowners approach this meeting as a presentation to be passively received, when it should be an active assessment of the designer's suitability for their project. The questions you ask in this meeting will tell you more about the designer than their portfolio alone.</p>
<p>Here are 15 questions to ask every interior designer you meet, along with what good and concerning answers look like.</p>

<div class="info-box"><strong>ℹ️ Did You Know:</strong> Research from Singapore consumer protection organisations shows that homeowners who ask structured questions during ID consultations and check at least three references are 60% less likely to experience significant renovation disputes. Preparation pays.</div>

<h2>Questions About Credentials and Experience</h2>
<h3>1. Are you registered with HDB as a renovation contractor?</h3>
<p>For HDB flat renovation, this is non-negotiable. The correct answer is yes — they should be able to provide their HDB contractor registration number. A "no" or evasion means you cannot use them for HDB permit-required works.</p>
<h3>2. Are you CaseTrust or CaseTrust-RCMA accredited?</h3>
<p>CaseTrust accreditation indicates the firm has been vetted for financial integrity and ethical business practices. Not all reputable firms are CaseTrust-accredited, but it is a meaningful signal of accountability. Verify the claimed accreditation on the CASE website.</p>
<h3>3. How many years has the firm been in business, and can I see your ACRA registration?</h3>
<p>A new company (registered within 12 months) has no track record and may be a newly incorporated entity by directors who have previously operated under a different, problematic company name. Check their ACRA registration date on BizFile+.</p>
<h3>4. Can I visit two recently completed projects in person and speak with those clients?</h3>
<p>Portfolio photos can be curated, filtered, and even stolen. An in-person site visit and a direct conversation with past clients is the gold standard of reference checking. A confident, legitimate designer will facilitate this. Hesitation or inability to arrange references is a concern.</p>

<h2>Questions About Their Design Process</h2>
<h3>5. Walk me through your design process from briefing to handover.</h3>
<p>Look for a structured, clear process: initial brief, concept development, design presentation, quotation, contract, permit application, phased construction, and defect handover. Disorganised or vague answers suggest a chaotic project management approach.</p>
<h3>6. Who exactly will be designing my home — you personally, or a junior designer?</h3>
<p>In many mid-sized ID firms, the senior designer closes the sale but a junior designer executes the project. Knowing who will actually be your day-to-day contact is important — the quality of that person's work determines your outcome.</p>
<h3>7. How many projects are you (or your assigned designer) currently managing?</h3>
<p>A designer managing more than 8–10 concurrent projects is stretched thin. Project management quality degrades with volume. The honest answer to this question reveals how much attention your project will receive.</p>

<h2>Questions About Costs and Contracts</h2>
<h3>8. Can you provide a fully itemised quotation with material specifications?</h3>
<p>The correct answer is yes, always. Any resistance to itemisation is a red flag — it may mean the firm wants to obscure where your money is going or retain flexibility to substitute materials.</p>
<h3>9. What is your payment schedule?</h3>
<p>Standard and consumer-safe: 20–30% on contract signing, milestone payments at agreed project stages, and 5–10% retention upon satisfactory handover. Be wary of requests for 50%+ upfront or single large payments that do not align with project milestones.</p>
<h3>10. What is your process for variation orders — changes made after the contract is signed?</h3>
<p>Good answer: all variations are documented in writing with agreed costs before execution, signed by both parties. Concerning answer: "We'll sort it out at the end" or "Don't worry, we'll keep it reasonable."</p>

<h2>Questions About Timeline and Project Management</h2>
<h3>11. What is the realistic timeline for my project, and what causes delays?</h3>
<p>A realistic answer includes specific phases and durations, acknowledges that delays can come from permit approval times, material delivery, and subcontractor scheduling, and gives you honest expectations rather than an optimistic number designed to win the job.</p>
<h3>12. Who is the site supervisor for my project, and how often will they be on site?</h3>
<p>A dedicated site supervisor who visits daily or every other day is ideal. Firms that manage sites entirely remotely through WhatsApp photos tend to miss issues that require in-person assessment.</p>

<h2>Questions About After-Sales and Dispute Resolution</h2>
<h3>13. What is your defect liability period, and what does it cover?</h3>
<p>Standard industry practice: 12 months from handover for workmanship defects. Materials may have separate warranty periods from manufacturers. Get this in writing in your contract.</p>
<h3>14. How do you handle disputes if a client is unhappy with the work?</h3>
<p>Good answer: direct communication first, then escalation to management, then formal resolution channels (CaseTrust/CASE if applicable). Dismissive answer: "We don't have disputes because our work is perfect" — this is naive and concerning.</p>
<h3>15. Can you share at least one past client who had an issue during renovation and how it was resolved?</h3>
<p>This question reveals character. Every renovation has issues — the mark of a good firm is how they respond to them. A designer who can honestly share a past problem and how they resolved it to the client's satisfaction demonstrates accountability and professionalism.</p>

<blockquote>"I asked every ID I met: 'Tell me about a project that went wrong and how you fixed it.' Two couldn't answer. One gave me a genuine story about a tile delivery delay and how they sourced a replacement overnight to keep the schedule. That was the firm I went with. They were exactly as good under pressure as they promised." — Homeowner, 5-room BTO, Punggol</blockquote>

<hr>

<h3>ID Interview Scoring Guide</h3>
<div style="overflow-x:auto">
<table>
<thead><tr><th>Question Category</th><th>Green Flag Answer</th><th>Red Flag Answer</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>HDB registration</td><td>Yes — provides registration number</td><td>Hesitates or says "not needed"</td></tr>
<tr><td>CaseTrust</td><td>Yes — verifiable on CASE website</td><td>Claims it but can't verify</td></tr>
<tr><td>References</td><td>Offers 2+ site visits proactively</td><td>Only shows photos/Instagram</td></tr>
<tr><td>Payment schedule</td><td>Milestone-based, max 30% upfront</td><td>Requests 50%+ upfront</td></tr>
<tr><td>Variation orders</td><td>Always in writing, pre-agreed cost</td><td>"We'll sort it out later"</td></tr>
<tr><td>Dispute resolution</td><td>Clear escalation process</td><td>Dismisses the question</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>

<div class="pro-tip"><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> After the consultation, trust your gut as much as the answers. You are about to spend 3–6 months in a close working relationship with this person. If the communication feels off, if you feel dismissed or rushed, or if the designer seems to be selling rather than listening — these interpersonal signals matter as much as their credentials.</div>`,
